NBA jump shots: modeling and counterfactuals

James R Bland (https://sites.google.com/site/jamesbland/)

October 11, 2019

Recently, I had the pleasure of reading Andrew Gelmans blog post on golf putting, which got me thinking about whether one could take this model to data from other sports. Since late spring, I have been tinkering around with a dataset of shots in the 2016-2017 NBA regular season, so this is where I started.

The model

The simplest version of Andrew Gelmans model assumes that a golf putt, or in my case, a jump shot, can be modeled as attempting to put a ball of radius \(r\) across a circle of radius \(R\).

Source: https://mc-stan.org/users/documentation/case-studies/golf.html

The player attempts to aim directly at the circle, but is off by angle \(\theta\), which is distributed \(N(0,\sigma^2)\).

source: https://mc-stan.org/users/documentation/case-studies/golf.html

\(\sigma\) is the standard deviation of this angle error. Dr.Gelman shows that the probability of making a putt (for me, hitting a jump shot), is equal to: \[ p_j=2\Phi\left(\frac{\sin^{-1}((R-r))/x_j}{\sigma}\right)-1 \] where \(x_j\) is the distance to the hole (in my case, basket).

In this post, I use this model to assess the shot accuracy, measured by \(\sigma\), of all players in the NBA who took more than 10 shots during the 2016-2017 regular season.

Data

I use a freely-available dataset of shots in the 2016-2017 NBA regular season. From here, I discard:

  • all observations that do not have the string Jump in the shot description
  • players who took fewer than 10 jump shots in this season (the model has a hard time with these), and
  • all blocked shots.

This is what the data look like:

plt<-ggplot(data=Data,aes(x=x,y=y,color=Outcome))+geom_point()

Estimating the model in Stan

I run this Stan program on each player individually, and so have posterior simulations of each players \(\sigma\):

// NBAJumpShots.stan
functions {
   
              
}
data {
  // Tell Stan how to read in the data
  int NT; // Number of observations
  int y[NT]; // Shot success = 1
  vector[NT] x; // distance from basket
  real r;
  real R;
  
}
transformed data {
    vector[NT] threshold_angle = asin((R-r) ./ x);
}
parameters {
  real<lower=0,upper=pi()/2> sigma;

}
transformed parameters {
  
}
model {
    vector[NT] p = 2*Phi(threshold_angle / sigma) - 1;
    
  sigma ~ normal(0,pi()/6);
  y ~ bernoulli(p);


  }
generated quantities {
  real sigma_degrees = sigma * 180 / pi();
}

This is the same as Andrew Gelmans file, except that my prior for \(\sigma\) is \(N(0,\pi/6)\), truncated to \((0,\pi/2)\). As there are quite a few players who do not take many shots, the prior is much more important for pinning down \(\sigma\) for these people.

Results

Here is the histogram of the estimates of each players \(\sigma\)

Means<-aggregate(SimResults[,1:2],by=list(SimResults$Player),FUN=mean)
Means<-Means[,c(1,2,3)]
colnames(Means)<-c("Player","sigma","sigma_degrees")

plt<-ggplot(data=Means[Means$sigma_degrees<11 & is.na(Means$sigma)==FALSE,],aes(x=sigma_degrees))+geom_histogram(binwidth=0.5)
plt<-plt+theme_bw()+xlab("\U03C3 (degrees)")
plt

However, it may be a bit more meaningful to display this as the (estimated) probability of hitting a 3-point shot, standing on the 3-point line directly in front of the basket:

prb3<-aggregate(2*pnorm(asin((0.450-4.7*2.54/100)/7.24)/SimResults$sigma)-1,by=list(SimResults$Player),FUN=mean)

plt<-ggplot(data=prb3[is.na(prb3$x)==FALSE,],aes(x=x))+geom_histogram(bins=30)
plt<-plt+theme_bw()+xlab("Probability of making a 3-point shot")
plt

It may also be interesting to compare these estimates (i.e.difficulty-adjusted scoring probabilities) to players raw scoring probabilities:

mScored<-data.frame(aggregate(Data$Scored,by=list(Data$ShootPlayer),FUN=mean))
d<-merge(mScored,prb3,by.x="Group.1",by.y="Group.1")
colnames(d)<-c("Player","prbRaw","prb3")

plt<-ggplot(data=d,aes(y=prbRaw,x=prb3))+geom_point()
plt<-plt+ylab("Raw probability")+xlab("3-point probability")
plt<-plt+theme_bw()+geom_abline(intercept=0,slope=1)
plt
## Warning: Removed 40 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

That is, the horizontal coordinate of each point is a players estimated probability, when shooting from exactly the same spot. Players with points above the \(45^\circ\) line are scoring more frequently than the 3-point probability would suggest, meaning that they are taking easier shots.

A counterfactual

Here are the models average (over all shots, and all simulation draws) shot probability as a function of distance from the basket:

L<-seq(0.4,12,length=100)

ShotProb<-data.frame()
sigmaSim<-SimResults$sigma
sigmaSim<-sigmaSim[is.na(sigmaSim)==FALSE]
for (ll in 1:length(L)) {
  
  pll<-2*pnorm(asin((0.450-4.7*2.54/100)/L[ll])/sigmaSim)-1
  simProbM<-mean(pll)
  d<-data.frame(simProbM)
  d$L<-L[ll]
  ShotProb<-rbind(ShotProb,d)
}

plt<-ggplot(data=ShotProb,aes(x=L,y=simProbM))+geom_line()
plt<-plt+theme_bw()
plt<-plt+geom_vline(xintercept=7.24)+geom_vline(xintercept=(5.79-1.22),linetype=2)
plt <-plt+xlab("Distance from basket (m)")+ylab("Probability")
plt

The vertical lines are placed at the foul line (4.57m) and 3-point line (7.24m). This implies an expected value of a shot taken from each distance. What if we moved the 3-point line a bit?

EV<-data.frame()
v<-ShotProb$simProbM*2
v2<-data.frame(v,L)
v2$PointValue<-"2 points"
v<-ShotProb$simProbM*3
v3<-data.frame(v,L)
v3$PointValue<-"3 points"

EV<-rbind(v2,v3)

plt<-ggplot(data=EV,aes(x=L,y=v,color=PointValue,group=PointValue))+geom_line(size=2)
plt<-plt+theme_bw()
plt<-plt+geom_vline(xintercept=7.24)+geom_vline(xintercept=(5.79-1.22),linetype=2)
plt <-plt+xlab("Distance from basket (m)")+ylab("Expected value")
plt

That is, the expected value of a shot is equal to the height of the red line if a player is inside the 3-point line, and the blue line if they are outside it. The difference in heights shows us the marginal value of being a little bit further out if the player is standing just inside the 3-point, if the line was at the \(x\) coordinate. One peeve of recent NBA shooting patterns is the absence of shots taken from around the foul line (dashed vertical line). The model estimates that these shots have a slightly smaller expected value that shots taken from the 3-point line (solid vertical line). This, coupled with it probably being easier to get into a good, open shooting position at the 3-point line, means that it should not be surprising that hardly any jump shots are taken from around the foul line.

Maybe moving the 3-point line out to about 8-10m would be enough to appreciably increase the fraction of shots taken from around the foul line.

APPENDIX: Data wrangling and model estimation in R

# NBAJumpShots.R
# data source: https://www.kaggle.com/wh0801/NBA-16-17-regular-season-shot-log/version/1

rm(list=ls()) 
setwd("C:/Users/jbland/OneDrive - University of Toledo/General notes on structural Bayes/Sports")
library(foreign)
library(xtable)
library(ggplot2)
library(gganimate)
library(gifski)
library(png)
library("rstan") # observe startup messages
rstan_options(auto_write = TRUE)
Sys.setenv(LOCAL_CPPFLAGS = '-march=native')
options(mc.cores = parallel::detectCores())



TeamList<-read.csv('NBA16-17/NBA team name vs abbreviation.csv')[,1]
Data<-data.frame()
for (tt in 1:length(TeamList)) {
  D<-read.csv(paste('NBA16-17/shot log ', TeamList[tt],'.csv',sep=""))

  colnames(D)<-c("SelfPrevious","PlayerPosition","Home","locationX","OpponentPrevious","HomeTeam","ShotType","points","AwayTeam","locationY","time","date","ShootPlayer","TimeFrom","quarter","Outcome")
  D$TeamName<-TeamList[tt]
  # only look at jump shots
  D<-D[grepl("Jump",D$ShotType),]
  # remove NAs
  D<-D[is.na(D$locationX)==FALSE,]
  D<-D[is.na(D$locationY)==FALSE,]
  
  D$x<- D$locationX
  D$y<- D$locationY
  DateList<-unique(D$date)
  for (dd in 1:length(DateList)) {
      d<-D[D$date==DateList[dd] & D$quarter==1,]
    dim(d)
    mx<-mean(d$locationX<500)
    if (mx>0.5) { # team is shooting to the left in 1st quarter
      D$x[D$date==DateList[dd] & D$quarter <3]<-1000-D$locationX
      D$y[D$date==DateList[dd] & D$quarter <3]<- 500-D$locationY
    }
    if (mx<=0.5) { # team is shooting to the right in 1st quarter
      D$x[D$date==DateList[dd] & D$quarter >=3]<-1000-D$locationX
      D$y[D$date==DateList[dd] & D$quarter >=3]<- 500-D$locationY
    }
  }
  
  D$x<-1000-D$x
  D$y<-500-D$y
  
  
  Data<-rbind(Data,D)
}





# Convert into meters
Data$locationX<-Data$locationX*28.7/1000
Data$locationX<-Data$locationY*15.2/500
# convert into SI units
Data$x<-Data$x*28.7/1000
Data$y<-Data$y*15.2/500

# distance to basket (m)
# ring is 1.22m from the baseline
Data$r<-sqrt((Data$x-1.22)^2+(Data$y-250*15.2/500)^2)

# Ignore overtime
Data<-Data[Data$quarter<=4,]

plt<-ggplot(data=Data,aes(x=x,y=y,color=Outcome))+geom_point()
plt<-plt+transition_states(TeamName,transition_length=1,state_length=5)
plt<-plt+labs(title = '{closest_state}')+theme_bw()+ coord_fixed()
anim_save(plt,filename = "NBAShotOutcomes.gif")

PlayerList<-unique(Data$ShootPlayer)

# Drop blocked shots
Data<-Data[Data$Outcome!="BLOCKED",]
Data$Scored<-as.integer(Data$Outcome=="SCORED")

r<-4.7*2.54/100 # radius of basketball in meters
R<-0.450 # radius of basketball in meters

Data$angle<-asin((R-r)/ Data$r)

Data<-Data[is.na(Data$angle)==FALSE,]


SimResults<-data.frame()

for (ii in 1:length(PlayerList)) {
  d<-Data[Data$ShootPlayer==PlayerList[ii],]
  
  StanData<-list(NT=dim(d)[1],y=d$Scored,x=d$r,r=r,R=R)
  if (StanData$NT>=10) { # only look at players who took at least 10 jump shots
  Sim<-stan("NBAJumpShots.stan",data=StanData)
  
  sigma_degrees<-extract(Sim)$sigma_degrees
  sigma<-extract(Sim)$sigma
  }
  else {
    sigma<-NA
    sigma_degrees<-NA
  }
  S<-data.frame(sigma,sigma_degrees)
  S$Player<-PlayerList[ii]
  S$Team<-d[1,"TeamName"]
  S$Position<-d[1,"PlayerPosition"]
  
  SimResults<-rbind(SimResults,S)
  
  print(paste(ii,"of",length(PlayerList),", N =",StanData$NT,", p =",mean(StanData$y)))
  
}

saveRDS(SimResults,"C:/Users/jbland/Documents/Sports/NBAJumpShots_SimIndividual.rds")
saveRDS(Data,"C:/Users/jbland/Documents/Sports/NBAJumpShots_CleanedData.rds")
